Package com.rb.nonbiz.text

Class Strings

java.lang.Object
com.rb.nonbiz.text.Strings
public class Strings
extends java.lang.Object
Various versions of Java's String.format(java.lang.String, java.lang.Object...) methods, with the advantage that format(java.lang.String, java.lang.Object...) doesn't throw an exception if the format doesn't match its arguments.

We normally take a fail-fast approach. However, this flexibility is important, because the cost of an exception is too high compared to having the wrong contents in a string, since we rarely look at the contents of strings to make any decisions in our codebase.

    • format

      public static java.lang.String format​(java.lang.String template, java.lang.Object... args)
      A safer version of Java's String.format(String, Object...).

      This will throw if the arguments don't match the format - e.g. Strings.format("%s %s", "A") is OK. In addition, it will not throw if an argument is null. Even though our codebase avoids using nulls, it's safer to be resilient to nulls. The idea is that you don't want the code crashing because of a malformed log statement. A safer thing to use is this method, which will not throw, and print something reasonable if there are missing or extra arguments after the format string.

      The code is copied from Guava preconditions class, where it is package private (and therefore we can't just call it).

    • asSingleLine

      public static java.lang.String asSingleLine​(java.lang.String first, java.lang.String... rest)
      This is handy in situations where we need to create a multiline string, but want to avoid the ugliness of having plus signs in the Java code for concatenation, which messes up indentation.

      This also adds a space between any pair of consecutive lines, in the event that concatenating them would result in concatenating two words. This method is used for human-readable text, in case the code author forgot to add spaces between lines.

      The criterion for what counts as a problem is fairly strict. By limiting to alphabetic characters only, we also avoid adding an extra space in case the text is HTML, and we are concatenating a line that ends with a closing HTML tag with a next line that starts with an HTML opening tag.

    • lastCharacterIsAlphabetic

      public static boolean lastCharacterIsAlphabetic​(java.lang.String s)
      Returns true if the last character of the string is an alphabetic character. Returns false for an empty string, since an empty string doesn't have a last character.

    • firstCharacterIsAlphabetic

      public static boolean firstCharacterIsAlphabetic​(java.lang.String s)
      Returns true if the last character of the string is an alphabetic character. Returns false for an empty string, since an empty string doesn't have a last character.
